# ARCHITECTURE SPINE — NON-NEGOTIABLE STRUCTURE

This rule exists to guarantee a clean foundation: strict layers, one-way dependencies, single
sources of truth, and hard boundaries around every external service. Follow it on EVERY file.
If a change would violate a boundary, stop and restructure — do not "just make it work."

## THE LAYERS (STRICT, ONE-WAY FLOW)

```
HTTP request
  → route        (HTTP only: parse request, call controller, shape response. NO logic, NO db.)
  → controller   (thin orchestration: Zod-validate input, call service(s), map result to response)
  → service      (ALL business logic. Pure-ish, testable. Never imports routes/controllers. Never touches req/res.)
  → repo         (ALL database access via Drizzle. The ONLY layer allowed to import schema/db.)
  → db
```

**Dependency direction is one-way and downward.** A layer may only import the layer directly
below it (and `shared/`). NEVER:
- a route or controller querying the DB directly (must go through a repo)
- a service importing a route/controller, or reading `req`/`res`
- a repo containing business logic
- any circular import between modules

If you catch yourself writing a Drizzle query inside a route or controller, STOP — move it to a repo.
If you catch business logic inside a route or repo, STOP — move it to a service.

## SINGLE SOURCES OF TRUTH (NO CROSSED WIRES)

- **Environment variables:** accessed ONLY through `config/env.ts`, which Zod-validates all env at
  boot and FAILS FAST if anything is missing or malformed. NEVER read `process.env.X` anywhere else
  in the codebase. Import the typed config object instead.
- **Database schema:** lives ONLY in `shared/schema.ts`. Derive types from Drizzle's `$inferSelect`/
  `$inferInsert` — do not hand-write duplicate types.
- **Business constants** (expense categories, GL mapping, confidence threshold, nudge rules): live
  ONLY in `shared/constants.ts`. Never duplicate a category string or threshold anywhere.
- **Runtime/business settings** (commission rates, bonus amounts): live in the `settings` table,
  read through a single settings service. Never hardcoded.

## INTEGRATION BOUNDARIES (ONE DOOR PER VENDOR)

Each external service gets exactly ONE integration module under `server/integrations/`. Nothing
outside that module may import the vendor SDK or know the vendor's data shape.

| Vendor | The only module allowed to call it |
|---|---|
| Anthropic Claude | `integrations/anthropic.ts` |
| Porter (CSV/API) | `integrations/porterIngestion.ts` (via `PorterIngestionService`) |
| QuickBooks Online | `integrations/quickbooks.ts` |
| Twilio | `integrations/twilio.ts` |
| Resend | `integrations/resend.ts` |
| Cloudflare R2 | `integrations/storage.ts` |

Services call these modules through small, typed interfaces — they receive normalized data, never
raw vendor payloads. This is what makes the vendors swappable and the wiring un-crossable. (Porter
especially: everything downstream consumes `NormalizedPorterAppointment`, never a CSV row.)

## VALIDATION AT EVERY BOUNDARY

Trust nothing that crosses into the system. Zod-validate and coerce at each edge:
- incoming API request bodies/params (in the controller)
- AI model output (after `JSON.parse`, before use)
- Porter CSV rows (in `mapPorterRow()`)
- environment (in `config/env.ts`)

## ERROR HANDLING (UNIFORM)

- One `AppError` class (in `utils/errors.ts`) with a status code and a safe message.
- Services throw typed `AppError`s. Integration modules catch vendor errors and rethrow as `AppError`.
- ONE global Express error middleware formats the response. Do NOT scatter ad-hoc `try/catch` that
  swallows errors or returns inconsistent shapes.
- No floating promises. `await` everything; no unhandled rejections.

## NAMING & EXPORTS

- **Named exports only. No default exports** (keeps renames safe and imports greppable).
- One primary responsibility per file. Soft cap ~300–400 lines — past that, split by responsibility.
- TypeScript strict. **No `any`** — use `unknown` + narrowing, or a real type.
- Match the reference codebase's file naming (camelCase: `revenueRepo.ts`, `artistAnalytics.ts`).

## DATABASE & MIGRATIONS

- Schema changes happen ONLY through Drizzle Kit migrations, committed to git.
- NEVER `db push` against production. NEVER hand-write ad-hoc SQL migrations.
- Every tenant-scoped query filters on the tenant key — enforced in the repo layer, not per-call.

## ANTI-DEBT RULES

- Don't port reference code you don't use — no dead code from GCOps/B.O.S.S. carried along.
- Rule of three: don't abstract until a pattern repeats 3×; but don't copy-paste a 3rd time either.
- Every new service gets unit tests; every new route gets an integration test (v2 §10).
- If two pieces of code need the same value, they import it from one place — they never each define it.
